==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*frijōnd-'', originally a present participle of the weak verb ''*frijōn-'' ‘to love, to free’ (Old English [[freogan|frēoġan]]), from Indo-European ''*prāy-, *prēy-'' ‘like, love’.  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon [[friund]] (Dutch [[vriend]]), Old High German [[friunt]] (German [[Freund]]), Old Norse [[frǫndi]] (Swedish [[frände]]), Gothic [[𐍆𐍂𐌹𐌾𐍉𐌽𐌳𐍃]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πραυς]], Slavonic ''*prьjatī'' (Old Church Slavonic [[прити]], Russian [[приять]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /fɹe:ond/

===Noun===
'''frēond''' ''m'' (''pl'' '''frēondas''' or '''frȳnd''')
# a [[friend]]
#:''Se hlaford ne scrifþ freonde ne feonde'': the lord regards neither friend nor foe.

